The essential charges against Sam Bankman-Fried are:
=09Customers deposited billions of dollars at his crypto exchange, FTX, to =
buy crypto.=09Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s trading firm, Alameda Research,=C2=A0=
secretly took that money to gamble on crypto tokens and make weird illiquid=
 venture investments.=09Also a lot of the money seems to have been siphoned=
 off to make political donations, buy celebrity endorsements, pay for Baham=
as real estate for Bankman-Fried and his family, etc.=09When=C2=A0customers=
 started asking for their money back last November, it wasn=E2=80=99t there=
.

This is bad! The basic combination of =E2=80=9Cthe customers=E2=80=99 money=
 is=C2=A0gone=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cyou lived in a $30 million penthouse=E2=
=80=9D is really killer. That=E2=80=99s the most basic outline of a financi=
al fraud: The customers don=E2=80=99t have the money anymore, and you do.
But Bankman-Fried is going to trial tomorrow, and here=E2=80=99s  Michael L=
ewis on=C2=A060 Minutes=C2=A0being asked =E2=80=9Cdo you think he knowingly=
 stole customers=E2=80=99 money=E2=80=9D and answering =E2=80=9Cput that wa=
y, no.=E2=80=9D So I suppose there will be=C2=A0a defense.
What is the defense? I think the defense is roughly:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe cryp=
to market crashed, there was a run on the bank, and the run on the bank is =
what evaporated the customers=E2=80=99 money. It was an accident, perhaps a=
 careless accident, but not theft.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0This is a very hard defense to pull off!
The first thing that is hard about it is that it is not at all intuitive th=
at a =E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=9D should be=C2=A0possible at a=C2=A0cr=
ypto exchange like FTX. The   intuitive way for a crypto exchange to work i=
s:
=09I deposit $100.=09I buy $100 of Bitcoin on the exchange.=09The exchange =
has $100 of Bitcoin earmarked for me.=09When I go to withdraw my $100 of Bi=
tcoin, if it=E2=80=99s not there, that means someone stole it.

FTX mostly did not work this way. It was a=C2=A0futures=C2=A0exchange. The =
  way it worked was more like:
=09I deposit $100.=09I use that to make a bet on $1,000 of Bitcoin.=09The e=
xchange has my $100 of collateral, but the $1,000 of Bitcoin isn=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0there; there=E2=80=99s=C2=A0just a bet between me and another custome=
r.=09If Bitcoin goes up 20%, that $1,000 of Bitcoin=C2=A0is now worth $1,20=
0, and my $100 bet is now worth $300.=09Similarly the=C2=A0other=C2=A0guy, =
the person who bet against me, put up $100 of collateral to bet against $1,=
000 of Bitcoin; now Bitcoin has gone up and his $100 bet is worth negative =
$100.=09When I go to withdraw the $300, if it=E2=80=99s not there, that mea=
ns that the person on the losing side of the bet didn=E2=80=99t pay up =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0or that the people on the losing side of some=C2=A0other=C2=A0b=
et on the exchange didn=E2=80=99t pay up, leaving the exchange without enou=
gh money to pay me.

The exchange sits between winners and losers of bets, and it can=E2=80=99t =
pay out what it owes to customers unless the customers who owe it money pay=
 up. Ordinarily the customers post collateral, the exchange risk-manages th=
e positions, etc., so there=E2=80=99s no problem, but in a sudden dramatic =
market move it is=C2=A0possible=C2=A0for the exchange not to have enough mo=
ney. This really does happen in legitimate regulated exchanges; it   kind o=
f almost=C2=A0happened on the London Metal Exchange last year.=C2=A0
But nobody believes this; this is already vastly more complicated than a ju=
ry is going to want to hear. Intuitively, if you take customer cash, you ou=
ght to have the cash, and if you don=E2=80=99t that looks fishy. (It does n=
ot help that FTX customers with only cash accounts, including those on FTX.=
US that were really   supposed to be all-cash and segregated, are also trap=
ped in bankruptcy.)
Even once you have convinced a jury that a run on the bank is=C2=A0possible=
, this defense runs into lots of problems. I want to mention three, though =
it should not be hard to think of more.
One: It is just not the case that some moves in crypto prices wiped out a b=
unch of FTX customers, leaving them owing FTX and leaving FTX unable to pay=
 off its other customers. Some moves in crypto prices wiped out=C2=A0one=C2=
=A0FTX customer: Alameda. It turned out that Alameda had massive amounts of=
 under- or uncollateralized debt to FTX: When the customer money wasn=E2=80=
=99t there, it was pretty much entirely because Alameda had lost it.
That right there is suspicious: If the basic economic structure of the exch=
ange was that it owed all of its customers money,=C2=A0except=C2=A0that its=
 biggest customer, a trading firm owned by the exchange=E2=80=99s chief exe=
cutive officer, owed=C2=A0it=C2=A0money, then that=E2=80=99s bad. Structura=
lly that is just =E2=80=9Cwe take money from customers and use it for our o=
wn gambling.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
But also every detail=C2=A0of how that worked is really bad. Alameda owed F=
TX a bunch of money, but nobody else did =E2=80=94=C2=A0nobody else got wip=
ed out by huge price moves leaving it in an uncollateralized negative posit=
ion to FTX =E2=80=94=C2=A0because FTX=C2=A0did=C2=A0have reasonable risk ma=
nagement systems. If you ran some unaffiliated hedge fund and you wanted to=
 put up $20 of your own money and borrow $1 billion from FTX to buy some il=
liquid volatile speculative crypto token, FTX=E2=80=99s computers would say=
 =E2=80=9Cabsolutely not.=E2=80=9D This was a point of pride at FTX, a thin=
g that they advertised, a thing that they touted to regulators and Congress=
 and that Bankman-Fried tweeted about.
But=C2=A0Alameda=C2=A0was allowed to do that: There were settings in FTX=E2=
=80=99s code that allowed Alameda to have an infinite negative balance, to =
borrow freely with no collateral. And Alameda drew on this=C2=A0during last=
 year=E2=80=99s crypto market crash, as it was having a hard time borrowing=
 elsewhere.=C2=A0A key part of the trial will be about whether Bankman-Frie=
d authorized this. =E2=80=9CBankman-Fried was adamant,=E2=80=9D in  talking=
 to Sheelah Kolhatkar at the New Yorker,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthat prosecutors wou=
ld not be able to produce any documents showing him authorizing the unlimit=
ed borrowing, because, he says, there are none.=E2=80=9D But basically ever=
yone else who worked at FTX will  probably testify that he did. This is ver=
y self-interested testimony: The deal prosecutors offered them is implicitl=
y something close to =E2=80=9Cif you say Bankman-Fried did it, you can prob=
ably avoid prison, and if you don=E2=80=99t we will probably send you to pr=
ison forever.=E2=80=9D Still it doesn=E2=80=99t help him, and the prosecuto=
rs  seem to have recordings of his colleagues saying that=C2=A0before=C2=A0=
the government stepped in.
Two: It is not just that Alameda made a bunch of bets on cryptocurrency tra=
des that all happened to move against it at once. Alameda did not get blown=
 up by, like, a cross-border Bitcoin arbitrage gone wrong, or even really b=
y the Terra/Luna collapse that brought down so many other crypto firms.
  [2]
=C2=A0Alameda=E2=80=99s troubles, at the end, were really that it owed bill=
ions of dollars to FTX (and its customers), and its assets consisted largel=
y of weird illiquid FTX-affiliated stuff. FTT tokens, and SRM tokens, and M=
APS and the rest: =E2=80=9CSamcoins=E2=80=9D that Bankman-Fried had invente=
d, that were mostly owned by Alameda, and that represented mostly bets on h=
is own ventures. Customers came to FTX to bet on Bitcoin and Ethereum and a=
ll sorts of other unaffiliated cryptocurrencies, and then Alameda=C2=A0took=
=C2=A0their money and chucked it all into bets on FTX=E2=80=99s own in-hous=
e cryptocurrencies.
There is something disturbingly Ponzi-ish about taking real customer money =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0dollars that customers gave you to bet on, sure, crypto, but=
 at least crypto that you don=E2=80=99t control =E2=80=94=C2=A0and using it=
 to prop up the prices of crypto tokens that you=C2=A0do=C2=A0control.   It=
 is the box. It is the idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0  which Bankman-Fried once expre=
ssed to me on a podcast =E2=80=94=C2=A0that you can just make up a cryptocu=
rrency, ascribe to it some arbitrary market value, and then borrow millions=
 of dollars against its fake market value.=C2=A0
Three: The facts are still unclear, and my assumption is that the vast majo=
rity of the $8 billion-ish of missing customer money went to Alameda, which=
 lost it on dumb crypto bets.
  [3]
=C2=A0But not all of it! Lewis says on=C2=A060 Minutes=C2=A0that Tom Brady =
got paid $55 million for endorsing FTX, and he was one of many highly paid =
celebrity endorsers. There were many millions of dollars spent on political=
 donations and effective altruism stuff and Bahamas real estate and the pro=
fligate operations of FTX.
You could imagine some sort of accounting in which all of those expenses we=
re rigorously paid for out of FTX=E2=80=99s operating income (from fees it =
legitimately charged customers for trading, and that they paid in cash), wh=
ile the $8 billion was lost entirely due to=C2=A0unfortunate mistakes in Al=
ameda=E2=80=99s leverage. But there=E2=80=99s no suggestion that any accoun=
ting like that=C2=A0exists, and everyone agrees that FTX=E2=80=99s actual a=
ccounting was cartoonishly bad. (=E2=80=9CFor example, employees of the FTX=
 Group submitted payment requests through an on-line =E2=80=98chat=E2=80=99=
 platform where a disparate group of supervisors approved disbursements by =
responding with personalized emojis,=E2=80=9D   complained its post-bankrup=
tcy CEO.)=C2=A0This makes it impossible to argue that all of these expenses=
 were paid for out of operating income rather than customer money.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
Instead what it looks like is that FTX and Alameda=C2=A0had a sort of undif=
ferentiated pot of money, awarded themselves enormous accounting income, an=
d then were untroubled about spending tens of millions of dollars on random=
 stuff because they figured there was so much more where that came from. Ba=
nkman-Fried=E2=80=99s defense has to be something like =E2=80=9Cwhen I look=
ed at our financial position as I understood it, I figured we had gajillion=
s of dollars more money than we owed to customers, so I figured there was n=
othing wrong with spending a few hundred million dollars on marketing and e=
mployee perks.=E2=80=9D
And, you know, maybe. FTX does seem to have made a lot of money in actual f=
ees.
  [4]
 For a while Alameda=C2=A0had, on paper, a giant balance sheet with a lot o=
f equity. Schematically, at the peak, FTX/Alameda might have had a pile of =
tokens with a market value =E2=80=94=C2=A0the last sale price of one token,=
 times the number of tokens FTX/Alameda held =E2=80=94=C2=A0of $100 billion=
, while it owed customers $30 billion of real or real-ish money (dollars, B=
itcoins, Ether, etc.).
  [5]
 Bankman-Fried could have looked at those numbers=C2=A0and thought =E2=80=
=9Cmeh, $100 billion is way more than $30 billion, we=E2=80=99re rich, we c=
an afford Tom Brady.=E2=80=9D
But that $100 billion was fake, in the sense that FTX/Alameda could not hav=
e gotten (and did not get) anything like $100 billion for those tokens, whi=
le the $30 billion was real, in the sense that the US government is trying =
to put Bankman-Fried in prison because the customers did not get their mone=
y back in full.
One problem with this defense, and with the =E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=
=9D defense generally, is that it requires a lot of optimism about crypto. =
It requires you to believe that Bankman-Fried looked at Alameda=E2=80=99s h=
uge stash of crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0a huge stash made up in part of crypto t=
okens that Bankman-Fried had invented, whose trading he and Alameda largely=
 controlled, whose market values were based largely on confidence in him =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and said =E2=80=9Cah yes, this is real money, I can go ahead=
 and spend this and still have plenty of real money to pay back my customer=
s=E2=80=99 dollars and Bitcoin and stuff.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I mean, here's a math problem:
=09You have $100 billion of weird crypto tokens.=09You owe people $30 billi=
on of real money.=09How much money do you have available to spend?

My answer would be =E2=80=9Ceep, nothing, I gotta pay back that $30 billion=
 as soon as possible before it all collapses and I go to prison.=E2=80=9D B=
ut that=E2=80=99s me! There are plenty of people in crypto who would say =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0or, at least, who would have said in 2022 =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cah great I have $70 billion, crypto is the future, $100 billion of ra=
ndom crypto is worth at least as much as $100 billion of debased fiat curre=
ncy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s just that Bankman-Fried never seemed to be one of them. I   wr=
ote once about my impression of him after the =E2=80=9Cbox=E2=80=9D podcast=
:
My view was, and is, that if you talk to a crypto exchange operator and he =
is like =E2=80=9Ccrypto is changing the world, your old-fashioned economics=
 are just FUD, HODL,=E2=80=9D then that=E2=80=99s bad. A wild-eyed crypto t=
rue believer is not the person to operate an exchange. The person you want =
operating an exchange is a clear-eyed=C2=A0trader. You want someone whose b=
asic attitude to financial assets is, like, =E2=80=9Cif someone wants to bu=
y and someone wants to sell, I will put them together and collect a fee.=E2=
=80=9D You want someone whose perspective is driven by markets, not ideolog=
y, who cares about risk, not futurism. A certain cynicism about the product=
