<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The essential charges against Sam Bankman-Frie=
d are:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Customers deposited billions of dollar=
s at his crypto exchange, FTX, to buy crypto.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s trading firm, Alameda Research,=C2=A0se=
cretly took that money to gamble on crypto tokens and make weird illiquid v=
enture investments.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also a lot of =
the money seems to have been siphoned off to make political donations, buy =
celebrity endorsements, pay for Bahamas real estate for Bankman-Fried and h=
is family, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When=C2=A0customer=
s started asking for their money back last November, it wasn=E2=80=99t ther=
e.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is bad! The basic combination of =E2=80=
=9Cthe customers=E2=80=99 money is=C2=A0gone=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cyou live=
d in a $30 million penthouse=E2=80=9D is really killer. That=E2=80=99s the =
most basic outline of a financial fraud: The customers don=E2=80=99t have t=
he money anymore, and you do.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Bankman-Fried is going to trial tomorrow, =
and here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2JzbmV3cy5jb20vdmlkZW8vc2FtLWJhbmttYW4tZn=
JpZWQtbWljaGFlbC1sZXdpcy1ib29rLTYwLW1pbnV0ZXMtdmlkZW8tMjAyMy0xMC0wMS8/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB20dae0a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Michael Lewis on=C2=A0</a><em><a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuY2JzbmV3cy5jb20vdmlkZW8vc2FtLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQtbWljaGFlbC1sZXdpcy1=
ib29rLTYwLW1pbnV0ZXMtdmlkZW8tMjAyMy0xMC0wMS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC20dae=
0a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">60 Minutes</a>=C2=A0</em>being asked =E2=80=9Cdo you think he =
knowingly stole customers=E2=80=99 money=E2=80=9D and answering =E2=80=9Cpu=
t that way, no.=E2=80=9D So I suppose there will be=C2=A0a defense.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is the defense? I think the defense is ro=
ughly:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe crypto market crashed, there was a run on the bank=
, and the run on the bank is what evaporated the customers=E2=80=99 money. =
It was an accident, perhaps a careless accident, but not <em>theft</em>.=E2=
=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This is a very hard defense to pull off!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first thing that is hard about it is that =
it is not at all intuitive that a =E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=9D should =
be=C2=A0<em>possible </em>at a=C2=A0crypto exchange like FTX. The <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1m=
cmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQxMDAyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMDImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBc40bbd5b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  intuitive way for a crypto exchange to work</a>=
 is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I deposit $100.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">I buy $100 of Bitcoin on the exchange.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The exchange has $100 of Bitcoin earmarked for me.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When I go to withdraw my $100 of =
Bitcoin, if it=E2=80=99s not there, that means someone stole it.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX mostly did not work this way. It was a=C2=
=A0<em>futures=C2=A0</em>exchange. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMTMvaG93LXRvLWRvLWZyYXVkLWF0LWEtZnV0dXJlcy1le=
GNoYW5nZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDAyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9z=
b3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMDImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d142b03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  way it worked</a> was more li=
ke:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I deposit $100.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">I use that to make a bet on $1,000 of Bitcoin.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The exchange has my $100 of collateral, bu=
t the $1,000 of Bitcoin isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>there</em>; there=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0just a bet between me and another customer.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">If Bitcoin goes up 20%, that $1,000 of Bitcoin=C2=A0is now =
worth $1,200, and my $100 bet is now worth $300.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Similarly the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>guy, the person who b=
et against me, put up $100 of collateral to bet against $1,000 of Bitcoin; =
now Bitcoin has gone up and his $100 bet is worth negative $100.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When I go to withdraw the $300, if it=E2=80=
=99s not there, that means that the person on the losing side of the bet di=
dn=E2=80=99t pay up =E2=80=94=C2=A0or that the people on the losing side of=
 some=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>bet on the exchange didn=E2=80=99t pay up, l=
eaving the exchange without enough money to pay me.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The exchange sits between winners and losers o=
f bets, and it can=E2=80=99t pay out what it owes to customers unless the c=
ustomers who owe it money pay up. Ordinarily the customers post collateral,=
 the exchange risk-manages the positions, etc., so there=E2=80=99s no probl=
em, but in a sudden dramatic market move it is=C2=A0<em>possible=C2=A0</em>=
for the exchange not to have enough money. This really does happen in legit=
imate regulated exchanges; it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMDcvbmlja2VsLWJpZy1zaG90LWNhbGxlZC10aGUtc2hvdHM_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMTAwMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB1eadd6e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  kind of almost=C2=A0happened</a> on the Lon=
don Metal Exchange last year.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But nobody believes this; this is already vast=
ly more complicated than a jury is going to want to hear. Intuitively, if y=
ou take customer cash, you ought to have the cash, and if you don=E2=80=99t=
 that looks fishy. (It does not help that FTX customers with only cash acco=
unts, including those on FTX.US that were really <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDEvc2JmLW1pc3NlZC1mdHgtcy1yaXNrcz9=
jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDAyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bm=
V3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMDImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB676cc811" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  supposed to be all-cash and segregated<=
/a>, are also trapped in bankruptcy.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even once you have convinced a jury that a run=
 on the bank is=C2=A0<em>possible</em>, this defense runs into lots of prob=
lems. I want to mention three, though it should not be hard to think of mor=
e.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One: It is just not the case that some moves i=
n crypto prices wiped out a bunch of FTX customers, leaving them owing FTX =
and leaving FTX unable to pay off its other customers. Some moves in crypto=
 prices wiped out=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>FTX customer: Alameda. It turned o=
ut that Alameda had massive amounts of under- or uncollateralized debt to F=
TX: When the customer money wasn=E2=80=99t there, it was pretty much entire=
ly because Alameda had lost it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That right there is suspicious: If the basic e=
conomic structure of the exchange was that it owed all of its customers mon=
ey,=C2=A0<em>except=C2=A0</em>that its biggest customer, a trading firm own=
ed by the exchange=E2=80=99s chief executive officer, owed=C2=A0<em>it=C2=
=A0</em>money, then that=E2=80=99s bad. Structurally that is just =E2=80=9C=
we take money from customers and use it for our own gambling.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But also every detail=C2=A0of how that worked =
is really bad. Alameda owed FTX a bunch of money, but nobody else did =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0nobody else got wiped out by huge price moves leaving it in an =
uncollateralized negative position to FTX =E2=80=94=C2=A0because FTX=C2=A0<=
em>did=C2=A0</em>have reasonable risk management systems. If you ran some u=
naffiliated hedge fund and you wanted to put up $20 of your own money and b=
orrow $1 billion from FTX to buy some illiquid volatile speculative crypto =
token, FTX=E2=80=99s computers would say =E2=80=9Cabsolutely not.=E2=80=9D =
This was a point of pride at FTX, a thing that they advertised, a thing tha=
t they touted to regulators and Congress and that Bankman-Fried tweeted abo=
ut.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0<em>Alameda=C2=A0</em><a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMTMvaG93LXRvLWRvLWZyYXVk=
LWF0LWEtZnV0dXJlcy1leGNoYW5nZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDAyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWV=
kaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMDImdXRtX2NhbX=
BhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4d142b03" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">was allowe=
d to do that</a>: There were settings in FTX=E2=80=99s code that allowed Al=
ameda to have an infinite negative balance, to borrow freely with no collat=
eral. And Alameda drew on this=C2=A0during last year=E2=80=99s crypto marke=
t crash, as it was having a hard time borrowing elsewhere.=C2=A0A key part =
of the trial will be about whether Bankman-Fried authorized this. =E2=80=9C=
Bankman-Fried was adamant,=E2=80=9D in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2VyLmNvbS9tYW=
