<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two: It is not just that Alameda made a bunch =
of bets on cryptocurrency trades that all happened to move against it at on=
ce. Alameda did not get blown up by, like, a cross-border Bitcoin arbitrage=
 gone wrong, or even really by the Terra/Luna collapse that brought down so=
 many other crypto firms.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Alameda=E2=80=99s troubles, at the end, were really that it owed =
billions of dollars to FTX (and its customers), and its assets consisted la=
rgely of weird illiquid FTX-affiliated stuff. FTT tokens, and SRM tokens, a=
nd MAPS and the rest: =E2=80=9CSamcoins=E2=80=9D that Bankman-Fried had inv=
ented, that were mostly owned by Alameda, and that represented mostly bets =
on his own ventures. Customers came to FTX to bet on Bitcoin and Ethereum a=
nd all sorts of other unaffiliated cryptocurrencies, and then Alameda=C2=A0=
took=C2=A0their money and chucked it all into bets on FTX=E2=80=99s own in-=
house cryptocurrencies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is something disturbingly Ponzi-ish abou=
t taking real customer money =E2=80=94=C2=A0dollars that customers gave you=
 to bet on, sure, crypto, but at least crypto that you don=E2=80=99t contro=
l =E2=80=94=C2=A0and using it to prop up the prices of crypto tokens that y=
ou=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>control. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPU=
