et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  complained its post-bankruptcy CEO</a>.)=
=C2=A0This makes it impossible to argue that all of these expenses were pai=
d for out of operating income rather than customer money.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead what it looks like is that FTX and Ala=
meda=C2=A0had a sort of undifferentiated pot of money, awarded themselves e=
normous accounting income, and then were untroubled about spending tens of =
millions of dollars on random stuff because they figured there was so much =
more where that came from. Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s defense has to be someth=
ing like =E2=80=9Cwhen I looked at our financial position as I understood i=
t, I figured we had gajillions of dollars more money than we owed to custom=
ers, so I figured there was nothing wrong with spending a few hundred milli=
on dollars on marketing and employee perks.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, you know, maybe. FTX does seem to have ma=
de a lot of money in actual fees.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[4]</span>
</a> For a while Alameda=C2=A0had, on paper, a giant balance sheet with a l=
ot of equity. Schematically, at the peak, FTX/Alameda might have had a pile=
 of tokens with a market value =E2=80=94=C2=A0the last sale price of one to=
ken, times the number of tokens FTX/Alameda held =E2=80=94=C2=A0of $100 bil=
lion, while it owed customers $30 billion of real or real-ish money (dollar=
s, Bitcoins, Ether, etc.).<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> Bankman-Fried could have looked at those numbers=C2=A0and thought =E2=
=80=9Cmeh, $100 billion is way more than $30 billion, we=E2=80=99re rich, w=
e can afford Tom Brady.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that $100 billion was fake, in the sense t=
hat FTX/Alameda could not have gotten (and did not get) anything like $100 =
billion for those tokens, while the $30 billion was real, in the sense that=
 the US government is trying to put Bankman-Fried in prison because the cus=
tomers did not get their money back in full.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One problem with this defense, and with the =
=E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=9D defense generally, is that it requires a =
lot of optimism about crypto. It requires you to believe that Bankman-Fried=
 looked at Alameda=E2=80=99s huge stash of crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0a huge sta=
sh made up in part of crypto tokens that Bankman-Fried had invented, whose =
trading he and Alameda largely controlled, whose market values were based l=
argely on confidence in him =E2=80=94=C2=A0and said =E2=80=9Cah yes, this i=
s real money, I can go ahead and spend this and still have plenty of real m=
oney to pay back my customers=E2=80=99 dollars and Bitcoin and stuff.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, here's a math problem:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have $100 billion of weird crypto =
tokens.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You owe people $30 billion=
 of real money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">How much money do =
you have available to spend?</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>My</em> answer would be =E2=80=9Ceep, noth=
ing, I gotta pay back that $30 billion as soon as possible before it all co=
llapses and I go to prison.=E2=80=9D But that=E2=80=99s me! There are plent=
y of people in crypto who would say =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, at least, who would =
have said in 2022 =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cah great I have $70 billion, cryp=
to is the future, $100 billion of random crypto is worth at least as much a=
s $100 billion of debased fiat currency.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s just that Bankman-Fried never see=
med to be one of them. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/32899702.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTAvZnR4LWlzLXN0aWxsLWxvb2tpbmctZm9yLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDE=
wMDIyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTAwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB18c94913" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">  wrote once</a> about my impression of him after the =
=E2=80=9Cbox=E2=80=9D podcast:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My view was, and is, that if you t=
alk to a crypto exchange operator and he is like =E2=80=9Ccrypto is changin=
g the world, your old-fashioned economics are just FUD, HODL,=E2=80=9D then=
 that=E2=80=99s bad. A wild-eyed crypto true believer is not the person to =
operate an exchange. The person you want operating an exchange is a clear-e=
yed=C2=A0<em>trader</em>. You want someone whose basic attitude to financia=
l assets is, like, =E2=80=9Cif someone wants to buy and someone wants to se=
ll, I will put them together and collect a fee.=E2=80=9D You want someone w=
hose perspective is driven by markets, not ideology, who cares about risk, =
not futurism. A certain cynicism about the products he is trading is probab=
ly healthy.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well. It would have been! If you were skeptica=
l about the value of your giant stash of crypto, you wouldn=E2=80=99t borro=
w customer money against it, and you wouldn=E2=80=99t keep spending real mo=
ney on endorsements and donations. You=E2=80=99d only do that if (1) you we=
re naively optimistic about the value of your crypto or (2) you were=C2=A0<=
em>extremely=C2=A0</em>cynical, and stealing it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The defense is that Bankman-Fried was incredib=
ly naive. It not only requires you to believe=C2=A0that his=C2=A0lieutenant=
s were stealing all the customer money without him noticing, that he made a=
 series of innocent risk management mistakes while everyone else was buildi=
ng nefarious backdoors. It also requires you to believe that he believed in=
 his stash of crypto, that he thought his vast imaginary wealth was real an=
d his to spend. Obviously it turned out not to be.</p>
